<div id="review_3932949240" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/3932949240" />
    <a title="Tanya" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/272677-tanya"><img alt="Tanya" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1536781085p2/272677.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/3932949240?book_show_action=true">Jun 22, 2021</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Tanya" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Tanya" href="/user/show/272677-tanya">Tanya</a>
      </span>

          added it


          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Mass Market Paperback 9782253096344" href="/book/show/50627233-les-mis-rables">review of another edition</a>


        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/272677-tanya?shelf=books-in-french">books-in-french</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3932949240" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer15997931447492877911">“Aimez-vous bien toujours. Il n’y a guère autre chose que cela dans le monde: s’aimer.” // “Love each other well and always. There is nothing else but that in the world: love for each other.”<br/><br/>That’s a wrap!! It took 6 months but I read the last page of Les Misérables in French last night. ❤️<br/><br/>When I finished my 20 minutes of Les Mis on Friday afternoon and realized I only had about 30 pages left, I freaked out a little bit. Reading this book has become such a big part of my daily routine. There wer</span>
  <span id="freeText15997931447492877911" style="display:none">“Aimez-vous bien toujours. Il n’y a guère autre chose que cela dans le monde: s’aimer.” // “Love each other well and always. There is nothing else but that in the world: love for each other.”<br /><br />That’s a wrap!! It took 6 months but I read the last page of Les Misérables in French last night. ❤️<br /><br />When I finished my 20 minutes of Les Mis on Friday afternoon and realized I only had about 30 pages left, I freaked out a little bit. Reading this book has become such a big part of my daily routine. There were certainly days when it felt like I was just checking another box on the to-do list, but most days it brought me so much joy. I am going to miss it. <br /><br />I wanted to really savor reading this last section. After seeing the musical multiple times and bawling at the ending each time, I knew I needed to give myself the time and space to really absorb it. The last time I saw the stage musical was in Lausanne, and it was in French, which gave me the idea to one day read the book in French. I was pregnant with my youngest at the time. Eleven years later….lol.<br /><br />I have so many feelings. I’ve read my share of classics but this one is so unique in its scope. There is so much depth to every character. Hugo can definitely ramble and there are chapters that to go on for pages about things that did not seem to matter to the story, but they always tied in somehow. <br /><br />It was so worth it to read the unabridged version. And it was SO worth it to read it in French, something I never thought I’d be able to do. Reading in English is a pleasure for me and so is reading in French, but it is more work. I now know that all French is equally challenging, no matter what century it was written in, for me at least. 😊 <br /><br />Les Misérables is above all a story of redemption. Jean Valjean is inspired to change his life after an act of grace and forgiveness. All of the characters are so vivid to me now. Reading Fantine’s backstory brought so much joy and then broke my heart. The evil Thenadiers show such a stark contrast to Valjean’s inherent goodness. Javert’s internal struggles were surprisingly emotional for me to read. Marius and Cosette are so ridiculously in love that they are blind to everything else. Enjolas, Marius and the students fighting at the barricade - their dedication to the revolution was heartbreaking and inspiring. Eponine and Gavroche are good people in spite of their parents. Valjean’s love for Cosette and how he puts her safety and happiness above everything else. I could go on and on. <br /><br />This will *definitely* forever be one of my favorite books of all time. I know it’s “just reading” but it feels like a big and unique reading experience. ❤️</span>
  <a data-text-id="15997931447492877911" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


