  <div class="friendReviews elementListBrown" >
    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_3283747761" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/3283747761" />
    <a title="L.H. Beynon" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/40382576-l-h-beynon"><img alt="L.H. Beynon" src="https://s.gr-assets.com/assets/nophoto/user/u_50x66-632230dc9882b4352d753eedf9396530.png" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/3283747761?book_show_action=true">May 16, 2020</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="L.H. Beynon" class="user" itemprop="url" name="L.H. Beynon" href="/user/show/40382576-l-h-beynon">L.H. Beynon</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
                  <em>
                    This review has been hidden because it contains spoilers. To view it,
                    <a href="#" onclick="Effect.toggle(&#39;reviewTextContainer3283747761&#39;); return false;">click here.</a>
                  </em>
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3283747761" class="readable"
                    style="display:none"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer3310308102103317563">The second half of this novel was, in my opinion, better paced. There were fewer annoying asides - although there were still too many. <br/><br/>There were a lot of silly coincidences, which became tiresome. These were mostly to do with Thernardier turning up at the most unlikely and convenient points - none more so than at the end! Having said that, the fact that he never really got his comeuppance was, while not satisfying, realistic, which I liked. <br/><br/>Cosette was not a well fleshed-out character. I know t</span>
  <span id="freeText3310308102103317563" style="display:none">The second half of this novel was, in my opinion, better paced. There were fewer annoying asides - although there were still too many. <br /><br />There were a lot of silly coincidences, which became tiresome. These were mostly to do with Thernardier turning up at the most unlikely and convenient points - none more so than at the end! Having said that, the fact that he never really got his comeuppance was, while not satisfying, realistic, which I liked. <br /><br />Cosette was not a well fleshed-out character. I know that this novel was a product of it's time, but she was just an empty vessel for the men in her life. There are moments when her characters is completely subsumed by Jean Valjean and Marius. She was infuriatingly infantalised. Even as a married adult, she was left out of important decisions. Ultimately, she felt like a prize for both Jean Valjean and Marius, which was disappointing. <br /><br />Jean Valjean's constant selflessness - apart from just once, while he was trying to keep Cosette and Marius apart - became highly frustrating, especially towards the end of the novel. However, I was pleased to see this called out by Marius.<br /><br />Marius was a strange character, who I started off not liking, came to like a little, began to hate and who, ultimately, I came to respect. I like the fact that he redeemed himself at the end of the novel, when he realised that he had been judging Valjean based on half-baked information, which was highly lacking in important details.<br /><br />However, this part of the novel was amazingly emotional. *Spoilers ahead*. <br /><br />The deaths of Eponine, Gavroche, Javert and Jean Valjean were very poignant and tragic:<br /><br />Eponine's sacrifices for a love who didn't love her back, were heartbreaking. Her death was pathetic and a good way to show what she had become. <br /><br />Gavroche was naturally generous and kind. He was, in a way, what Jean Valjean should have been. Not self-destructively selfless, but kind, generous, free, moral but practical. He didn't need to justify looking after himself. His death, after such a triumphant feet in helping the rebels, was shocking to read.<br /><br />I loved Javert. He was doing his duty. He always acted in the way that he thought right. He was clever and incorruptible. The moment that he realises how good Jean Valjean is, it makes him question the law, which is all he has stood for. He is destroyed by being saved by his nemesis. Allowing moral ambiguity into his life kills him. I was genuinely upset when he died.<br /><br />Jean Valjean's death was tragic and preventable, but ultimately quite cathartic. I was worried that he would die alone, but Marius and Cosette did a clichéd dash to the death bed and got there in time.<br /><br />I know that Hugo was trying to tell the story of the revolutions through the characters and he was showing the injustices of French society at that time, also through his characters. In my opinion, this worked very well, on the whole. What made this volume better than the first, for me, was that he showed more and told/lectured less. Even though parts of this book were infuriating, I couldn't help but care for the characters and want to know where the plot would take them. To me, that outweighs most of the other issues.<br /><br />Overall, I would recommend this novel. </span>
  <a data-text-id="3310308102103317563" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

