<span id="freeTextContainer17877255205356000263">Victor Hugo needs to remember that he is writing a novel, not a speech.<br/><br/>While there is thankfully less prude-shaming in this volume, I think the first one was by far more powerful in terms of words and events. This one basically felt like the Deathly Hallows in that it was just like, yeah, I know they all died horribly in battle, yes, all very sad, but look! They get married! That makes up for the pain they suffered! *rolls eyes* I had really been excited for the rebellion in this book, but the a</span>
  <span id="freeText17877255205356000263" style="display:none">Victor Hugo needs to remember that he is writing a novel, not a speech.<br /><br />While there is thankfully less prude-shaming in this volume, I think the first one was by far more powerful in terms of words and events. This one basically felt like the Deathly Hallows in that it was just like, yeah, I know they all died horribly in battle, yes, all very sad, but look! They get married! That makes up for the pain they suffered! *rolls eyes* I had really been excited for the rebellion in this book, but the amount of time Hugo spends telling us about his views rather than the actual story made it fall flat (not to mention the shallow ending). It would have been much more effective if he had left the morals for the end of the story or so. <a href="https://www.goodreads.com/author/show/128382.Leo_Tolstoy" title="Leo Tolstoy" rel="nofollow noopener">Leo Tolstoy</a> is much better at combining philosophy into his books, for even if you find his statements dull, they never take away from the stories. <br /><br /><b>Content Warnings:</b> Graphic violence/gore, war, crime. </span>
