        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer4477180632" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer16156443821627541887">it is quite obvious that some of us wouldn’t pick up Les Miserables for actually reading it by looking at the size of the novel. however, i’m not going to include critical literary analysis in my review. i’m focusing on certain statements and questions that kept me hooked till the end. here are a few things that stirred my heart in contemplation. <br/><br/>nobody asks a bread thief why did he steal from the bakery. nobody asks a mother how is she to feed her baby on her own. nobody asks a child if she’s i</span>
  <span id="freeText16156443821627541887" style="display:none">it is quite obvious that some of us wouldn’t pick up Les Miserables for actually reading it by looking at the size of the novel. however, i’m not going to include critical literary analysis in my review. i’m focusing on certain statements and questions that kept me hooked till the end. here are a few things that stirred my heart in contemplation. <br /><br />nobody asks a bread thief why did he steal from the bakery. nobody asks a mother how is she to feed her baby on her own. nobody asks a child if she’s in pain who has no guardian by her side. nobody asks the living why it is important to join a revolution and kiss their graves. nobody asks a criminal what it takes to step into the light after residing in darkness. nobody asks a man to what extent can he protect the ones he loves. such is the France of an epoch, now only existing in our memories. such is the story of Les Miserables. such is the heart clutching tale of reality molded into fiction. our greatest gift from God is our life and yet how valueless it becomes when the blood rushes to make a difference, to mark a revolution in history, to fight for freedom. standing in the face of death is like honor. and yet nobody asks whether innocent bloodshed was worth the sacrifice.<br /><br />this is a brief ‘non-literary’ analysis of Hugo’s novel minus all the digressions and descriptive chapters for those who want to find reasons/answers to such statements. he has created these characters whom one is ought to love, wail, empathize, sympathize, mourn, and remember for the rest of our lives. i would undeniably confess that Les Miserables covers a major part of my heart and i will continue to go back to these characters to cry in their misery, and to laugh in their joys.</span>
  <a data-text-id="16156443821627541887" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


